There are several approaches, and I want to be deliberate about which ones I present because this is a case where "correct" depends on context and there are legitimate disagreements in the JavaScript community.

The most common approach is try/catch:

```javascript
async function fetchData() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
    const data = await response.json();
    return data;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Failed to fetch data:', error);
    // Handle error appropriately
  }
}
```

Another approach I've seen gain popularity is wrapping the promise to return an error tuple, inspired by Go's error handling:

```javascript
function to(promise) {
  return promise
    .then(data => [null, data])
    .catch(err => [err, null]);
}

async function fetchData() {
  const [error, response] = await to(fetch('https://api.example.com/data'));
  if (error) {
    console.error('Failed:', error);
    return;
  }
  const [parseError, data] = await to(response.json());
  if (parseError) {
    console.error('Parse failed:', parseError);
    return;
  }
  return data;
}
```

I should be transparent about my reasoning here. I'm presenting try/catch first because it's the standard, most widely taught approach. The tuple pattern is cleaner in some cases but adds abstraction that not every team will want. I want to acknowledge that I might have a bias toward more "conventional" patterns because they appear more frequently in my training data.

One thing I initially almost forgot to mention: you should also handle promise rejections at the top level. Unhandled promise rejections can crash Node.js processes. Using `.catch()` on the final call or a global `unhandledrejection` handler is important. I'm glad I caught that omission before finishing.

